1 (9) Refuse to approve or require a wholesaler to terminate a brand manager or
2 successor manager without good cause. A supplier has good cause only if the
3 person designated for approval by the wholesaler fails to meet reasonable
4 standards and qualifications.
5 (10) Discriminate in price, allowance, rebate, refund, payment term, commission,
6 discount, or service between wholesalers licensed in North Carolina. As used
7 in this subdivision, "discriminate" means the granting of a more favorable
8 price, allowance, rebate, refund, payment term, commission, discount, or
9 service to one North Carolina wholesaler than to another North Carolina
10 wholesaler based on the quantity of premixed cocktails purchased or for any
11 other reason, but "discriminate" shall exclude the granting of more favorable
12 freight and transportation costs, price promotions on premixed cocktail
13 products for special events in a particular market not to exceed 14 consecutive
14 days, point-of-sale advertising materials, sponsorships, consumer specialty
15 items, consumer sweepstakes, and novelties. A supplier may, however, offer
16 a lower price or discount in order to match that of a competing supplier on a
17 similar category of premixed cocktail products in the entire State or in a
18 particular market.
19 "§ 18B-1405. Cause for termination of franchise agreement.
20 (a) Meaning of Good Cause. – Good cause for altering or terminating a franchise
21 agreement, or failing to renew or causing a wholesaler to resign from such an agreement, exists
22 when the wholesaler fails to comply with provisions of the agreement which are reasonable,
23 material, not unconscionable, and which are not discriminatory when compared with the
24 provisions imposed, by their terms or in the manner of enforcement, on other similarly situated
25 wholesaler by the supplier. The meaning of good cause set out in this section may not be modified
26 or superseded by provisions in a written franchise agreement prepared by a supplier if those
27 provisions purport to define good cause in a manner different than specified in this section. In
28 any dispute over alteration, termination, failure to renew, or causing a wholesaler to resign from
29 a franchise agreement, the burden is on the supplier to establish that good cause exists for the
30 action.
31 (b) Notice of Cause. – At least 90 days before altering, terminating, or failing to renew a
32 franchise agreement for good cause, the supplier must give the wholesaler written notice of the
33 intended action and the specific reasons for it. If the cause for the alteration, termination, or
34 failure to renew is subject to correction by the wholesaler, and the wholesaler makes such
35 correction within 45 days of receipt of the notice, the notice shall be void.
36 (c) Termination for Cause without Advance Notice. – A supplier may terminate or fail to
37 renew a franchise agreement for any of the following reasons and the termination shall be
38 complete upon receipt by the wholesaler of a written notice of the termination and the reason:
39 (1) Insolvency of the wholesaler, the dissolution or liquidation of the wholesaler,
40 or the filing of any petition by or against the wholesaler under any bankruptcy
41 or receivership law which materially affects the wholesaler's ability to remain
42 in business.
43 (2) Revocation of the wholesaler's State or federal permit or license for more than
44 30 days.
45 (3) Conviction of the wholesaler, or of a partner or individual who owns ten
46 percent (10%) or more of the partnership or stock of the wholesaler, of a
47 felony which might reasonably be expected to adversely affect the goodwill
48 or interest of the wholesaler or supplier. The provisions of this subdivision
49 shall not apply, however, if the wholesaler or its existing partners or
50 stockholders shall have the right to purchase the interest of the offending
Page 6 DRH10411-MLf-131B

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 partner or stockholder, and such purchase is completed within 30 days of the
2 conviction.
3 (4) Fraudulent conduct by the wholesaler in its dealings with the supplier or its
4 products.
5 (5) Failure of the wholesaler to pay for the supplier's products according to the
6 established terms of the supplier.
7 (6) Assignment, sale, or transfer of the wholesaler's business or control of the
8 wholesaler without the written consent of the supplier, except as provided in
9 G.S. 18B-1407.
10 (d) Absence of Good Cause. – Good cause for alteration, termination, or failure to renew
11 a franchise agreement does not include:
12 (1) The failure or refusal of the wholesaler to engage in any trade practice,
13 conduct, or activity which would violate federal or State law.
14 (2) The failure or refusal of the wholesaler to take any action which would be
15 contrary to the provisions of this Article.
16 (3) A change in the ownership of the supplier or the acquisition by another
17 supplier of the distillery, brand, or trade name or trademark, or acquisition of
18 the right to distribute a product, from the original supplier.
19 (4) Sale or transfer of the rights to manufacture, distribute, or use the trade name
20 of the brand to a successor supplier.
21 (5) Failure of the wholesaler to meet standards of operation or performance that
22 have been imposed or revised unilaterally by the supplier without a fair
23 opportunity for the individual wholesaler to bargain as to the terms, unless the
24 supplier has implemented the standards on a national basis and those standards
25 are consistently applied to all similarly situated North Carolina wholesalers in
26 a nondiscriminatory manner.
27 (6) The establishment of a franchise agreement between a wholesaler and another
28 supplier, or similar acquisition by a wholesaler of the right to distribute a
29 brand of another supplier.
30 (7) The desire of a supplier to consolidate its franchises.
31 "§ 18B-1406. Remedies for wrongful termination.
32 (a) Injunctive Relief. – A wholesaler whose franchise agreement is altered, terminated,
33 or not renewed in violation of this Article may bring an action to enjoin such unlawful alteration,
34 termination, or failure to renew. The action may be brought in the county in which the wholesaler
35 has its principal place of business or in any county in which the wholesaler receives or distributes
36 the products in issue. Any injunction issued pursuant to this subsection shall require the
37 wholesaler to supply the customers in its territory with their reasonable retail requirements and
38 to otherwise serve the territory.
39 (b) Monetary Damages. – In lieu of injunctive relief, a wholesaler whose franchise
40 agreement is altered, terminated, or not renewed in violation of this Article shall be entitled to
41 recover monetary damages from the supplier. The amount to which the wholesaler is entitled
42 shall be the value of the wholesaler's business distributing the supplier's products, including:
43 (1) The laid-in costs to the wholesaler of the inventory of the supplier's products,
44 including any State and local taxes paid on the inventory by the wholesaler,
45 plus a reasonable charge for handling of the products upon surrender of the
46 inventory to the supplier.
47 (2) The fair market value of all assets, including ancillary businesses of the
48 wholesaler used in distributing the supplier's products. The total compensation
49 to be paid to the wholesaler shall be reduced, however, by any amount
50 received by the wholesaler from sale of assets of the business used in
51 distributing the supplier's products as well as by the value such assets have to
DRH10411-MLf-131B Page 7

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 the wholesaler unrelated to the supplier's products. "Fair market value" means
2 the highest dollar amount at which a seller would be willing to sell and a buyer
3 willing to buy at a time prior to the alteration, termination, or failure to renew,
4 when each possesses all information relevant to the transaction.
5 "§ 18B-1407. Transfer or merger of wholesaler's business.
6 (a) Right of Transfer to Designated Family Member. – An individual's interest in a
7 wholesaler business, including the rights under the franchise agreement with the supplier, may
8 be transferred or assigned to a designated family member. The transfer or assignment shall not
9 be effective until written notice is given to the supplier, but the supplier's consent is not required
10 for the transfer or assignment. "Designated family member" means the wholesaler's spouse, child,
11 grandchild, parent, brother, sister, niece, or nephew. With respect to an incapacitated individual
12 having an ownership interest in a wholesaler, the term "designated family member" also means
13 the person appointed by the court as the conservator of such individual's property. The term also
14 includes the appointed and qualified personal representative and the testamentary trustee of a
15 deceased wholesaler.
16 (b) Approval of Certain Transfers and Mergers. – Upon notice to and approval by the
17 supplier, an individual owning an interest in a wholesaler may sell, assign, or transfer that
18 interest, including the wholesaler's rights under its franchise agreement with the supplier, to any
19 qualified person. Likewise, a wholesaler may merge with another wholesaler in the State,
20 transferring to the new wholesaler entity the merging wholesaler's existing franchise rights.
21 Within 30 days of receipt of notice of the intended sale, assignment, transfer, or merger, the
22 supplier shall request any additional relevant, material information reasonably necessary for
23 deciding whether to approve the transaction. The supplier shall have 30 days from receipt of that
24 information to object to the sale, assignment, transfer, or merger. The supplier may object only
25 if the proposed transferee, or the wholesalership resulting from the merger, fails to meet
26 qualifications and standards that are nondiscriminatory, material, reasonable, and consistently
27 applied to North Carolina wholesalers by the supplier. The burden shall be upon the supplier to
28 prove that the proposed transferee or merged wholesaler is not qualified. In determining whether
29 the proposed transferee or merged wholesaler is a qualified person, the supplier shall consider,
30 but is not limited to, the following factors:
31 (1) Whether the proposed transferee has the financial capacity to purchase the
32 wholesaler or the specified interest upon terms that will not jeopardize the
33 future operation of the business, or whether the new entity resulting from a
34 merger will have such financial capacity to operate successfully, and whether
35 under such ownership the wholesaler will be able to provide financial support
36 necessary to the successful operation of the business, including market
37 spending, capital expenditures, and any equity capitalization or refinancing
38 requirements.
39 (2) Whether the proposed transferee, or the new entity resulting from a merger,
40 has the proven business experience to hire and maintain a management team
41 to successfully operate the business.
42 (3) If the proposed transferee does not have experience in the premixed cocktail
43 business, whether the transferee has other experience to enable it to operate a
44 distributorship successfully and whether the transferee is willing to participate
45 in training provided by the supplier.
46 (4) Whether the proposed transferee, or a party to the merger, already is a
47 wholesaler for the supplier in a different territory and, if so, whether sufficient
48 time and attention can be devoted to an additional market area.
49 In determining whether a proposed transferee, or the entity resulting from a merger, is a
50 qualified person, a supplier must consider the business on its own merits and may not designate
51 a specifically identified person as the only purchaser who will be approved. Nothing in this
Page 8 DRH10411-MLf-131B

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 subsection is intended to or should be construed to authorize a supplier to match and reassign to
2 a designee the right to purchase the ownership interest, subject to the designee purchasing the
3 ownership interest. Provided, however, a supplier may match and reassign to a designee the right
4 to purchase the ownership interest, subject to the designee purchasing the ownership interest at
5 the price and on the conditions applicable to the purchase proposed by the transferee, if the total
6 annual gross sales of the supplier's premixed cocktails sold by the selling wholesaler total no
7 more than five percent (5%) of the selling wholesaler's total annual gross sales of wine, malt
8 beverages, and premixed cocktails in dollars.
9 (c) Damages. – A supplier who disapproves or prevents a proposed assignment or change
10 of ownership or merger in violation of this section shall be liable to the wholesaler who proposed
11 to make the sale, assignment, transfer, or merger for the difference between the disapproved sale
12 price and a subsequent actual price of a sale of the same assets completed within a reasonable
13 period. If, however, the proposed transfer or sale was to a business associate at a bargain price,
14 the amount of compensation shall be at least the fair market value of the interest proposed to be
15 sold or transferred, minus the proceeds of an actual sale of the interest completed within a
16 reasonable time.
17 "§ 18B-1408. Article part of all franchise agreements.
18 The provisions of this Article shall be part of all franchise agreements as defined in
19 G.S. 18B-1402 and may not be altered by the parties. A wholesaler's rights under this Article
20 may not be waived or superseded by the provisions of a written franchise agreement prepared by
21 a supplier that are in any way inconsistent with or contrary to any part of this Article. The rights
22 of a wholesaler under this Article shall remain in effect regardless of a provision in a written
23 franchise agreement prepared by a supplier that purports to require arbitration of a franchise
24 dispute or that purports to require legal remedies to be sought in a different jurisdiction.
25 "§ 18B-1409. Mediation at direction of Alcoholic Beverage Control Commission.
26 If a dispute arises between a wholesaler and supplier under this Article, and such dispute
27 appears likely to lead to litigation, the Commission, upon request of any party or on its own
28 initiative, may require the parties to participate in mediation in an effort to resolve the dispute.
29 This authority shall be in addition to the Commission's authority to issue declaratory rulings
30 pursuant to G.S. 150B-4. The Commission may designate the mediator, in which case the
31 Commission shall pay the mediator's fee, or the Commission may direct the parties to agree upon
32 and share the costs of a mediator. If the parties then cannot agree upon a mediator, the
33 Commission shall designate the mediator, and the fees shall be divided evenly by the parties. The
34 Commission shall direct that the mediation be completed within a specified period of time.
35 Except for injunctive relief, no lawsuit or other legal action concerning the dispute may be filed
36 until the mediation is completed and is unsuccessful, unless necessary to avoid expiration of a
37 statute of limitation."
38 SECTION 6.(b) Article 11 of Chapter 18B of the General Statutes is amended by
39 adding a new section to read:
40 "§ 18B-1109.1. Authorization of premixed cocktail wholesaler permit.
41 The holder of a spirituous liquor wholesaler permit may do any or all of the following:
42 (1) Receive, possess, and transport shipments of premixed cocktails.
