16 (3) An establishment with a brown-bagging permit as defined in
17 G.S. 18B-1001(7)."
18 SECTION 14.(b) This section becomes effective October 1, 2025, and applies to
19 fortified wine and spirituous liquor possessed and consumed on or after that date.
20
21 REVISE LAW GOVERNING GAME NIGHTS
22 SECTION 15.(a) G.S. 14-309.28 reads as rewritten:
23 "§ 14-309.28. Limits on game night events.
24 The following limitations apply to game night events:
25 (1) The number of game night events conducted or sponsored by an exempt
26 organization shall be limited to four 24 events per year.
27 …
28 (5) A qualified facility authorized to host a game night under this Part shall not
29 host more than two 24 game nights in any calendar month.year."
30 SECTION 15.(b) This section becomes effective October 1, 2025, and applies to
31 game nights conducted on or after that date.
32
33 REVISE LAW GOVERNING RAFFLES
34 SECTION 16.(a) G.S. 14-309.15 reads as rewritten:
35 "§ 14-309.15. Raffles.
36 (a) It is lawful for any nonprofit organization, candidate, political committee, or any
37 government entity within the State, to conduct raffles in accordance with this section. Each
38 regional or county chapter of a nonprofit organization is eligible to conduct raffles in accordance
39 with this section independently of its parent organization. Any person who conducts a raffle in
40 violation of any provision of this section is guilty of a Class 2 misdemeanor. Upon conviction
41 that person shall not conduct a raffle for a period of one year. It is lawful to participate in a raffle
42 conducted pursuant to this section. It is not a violation of State law to advertise a raffle conducted
43 in accordance with this section. A raffle conducted pursuant to this section is not "gambling."
44 For the purpose of this section, "candidate" and "political committee" have the meaning provided
45 by Article 22A of Chapter 163 of the General Statutes, who have filed organization reports under
46 that Article, and who are in good standing with the appropriate board of elections. Receipts and
47 expenditures of a raffle by a candidate or political committee shall be reported in accordance
48 with Article 22A of Chapter 163 of the General Statutes, and ticket purchases are contributions
49 within the meaning of that Article.
50 (b) For purposes of this section "raffle" means a The following definitions apply in this
51 section:
Page 18 DRH10411-MLf-131B

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (1) 50/50 raffle. – A raffle conducted by a nonprofit organization or any
2 government entity within the State whereby funds collected by sale of raffle
3 tickets are split evenly between the prize winner or winners and the nonprofit
4 organization or government entity after the raffle drawing.
5 (2) Candidate. – As defined in Article 22A of Chapter 163 of the General Statutes.
6 This term only includes candidates who have filed organization reports under
7 that Article and who are in good standing with the appropriate board of
8 elections.
9 (3) Net proceeds of a raffle. – The receipts less the cost of prizes awarded.
10 (4) Political committee. – As defined in Article 22A of Chapter 163 of the General
11 Statutes. This term only includes political committees that have filed
12 organization reports under that Article and that are in good standing with the
13 appropriate board of elections.
14 (5) Raffle. – A game in which the prize is won by random drawing of the name
15 or number of one or more persons purchasing chances.
16 (c) A nonprofit organization may hold no more than five raffles per year.
17 (d) Except as provided in subsection (g) of this section, the maximum cash prize that may
18 be offered or paid for any one raffle is one hundred twenty-five thousand dollars ($125,000) and
19 if merchandise is used as a prize, and it is not redeemable for cash, the maximum fair market
20 value of that prize may be one hundred twenty-five thousand dollars ($125,000). The total cash
21 prizes offered or paid by any nonprofit organization shall not exceed two hundred fifty thousand
22 dollars ($250,000) in any calendar year. The total fair market value of all prizes offered by any
23 nonprofit organization, either in cash or in merchandise that is not redeemable for cash, shall not
24 exceed two hundred fifty thousand dollars ($250,000) in any calendar year.
25 (e) Raffles shall not be conducted in conjunction with bingo.
26 (f) As used in this subsection, "net proceeds of a raffle" means the receipts less the cost
27 of prizes awarded. No less than ninety percent (90%) of the net proceeds of a raffle shall be used
28 by the nonprofit organization for charitable, religious, educational, civic, or other nonprofit
29 purposes. None of the net proceeds of the raffle shall be used to pay any person to conduct the
30 raffle, or to rent a building where the tickets are received or sold or the drawing is conducted.
31 (g) Real property may be offered as a prize in a raffle. Any nonprofit organization
32 offering real property as a prize in a raffle shall provide the property free from all liens, provide
33 an owner affidavit and indemnity agreement, and provide a title commitment for the property
34 and shall make that commitment available for inspection upon request. The total appraised value
35 of all real estate prizes offered by any nonprofit organization shall not exceed two million two
36 hundred fifty thousand dollars ($2,250,000) in any calendar year.
37 (h) Notwithstanding any other subsection of this section, it is lawful for a federally
38 insured depository institution to conduct a savings promotion raffle under G.S. 53C-6-20,
39 54-109.64, 54B-140, or 54C-180.
40 (i) The restrictions set forth in subsections (c) through (g) of this section do not apply to
41 50/50 raffles conducted by nonprofit organizations or government entities within the State."
42 SECTION 16.(b) This section becomes effective December 1, 2025, and applies to
43 offenses committed on or after that date.
44
45 SEVERABILITY CLAUSE AND EFFECTIVE DATE
46 SECTION 17.(a) If any provision of this act or the application thereof to any person
47 or circumstances is held invalid, such invalidity shall not affect other provisions or applications
48 of this act that can be given effect without the invalid provision or application and, to this end,
49 the provisions of this act are declared to be severable.
50 SECTION 17.(b) Except as otherwise provided, this act is effective when it becomes
51 law.
